&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ctrl + Spacebar&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ctrl + Spacebar&lt;/strong&gt; is the shortcut key in MS Word 2019 to remove manual character formatting from selected text.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This action resets the selected text back to the default font formatting of the applied style.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It removes formatting such as bold, italics, underline, font size, and font color, among others, while retaining the text content.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Using this shortcut ensures consistency in formatting, especially in documents with mixed styles.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a quick and efficient way to clean up unwanted manual formatting without affecting the structure of the document.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other Related Shortcut Keys in MS Word:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ctrl + Z:&lt;/strong&gt; Used to undo the last action or command in MS Word.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ctrl + B:&lt;/strong&gt; Toggles bold formatting for the selected text.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ctrl + Shift + N:&lt;/strong&gt; Applies the Normal style to the selected text, resetting both paragraph and character formatting.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ctrl + Spacebar:&lt;/strong&gt; Specifically removes manual character formatting while retaining the applied style&amp;rsquo;s default settings.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Importance of Removing Manual Formatting:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Helps maintain a uniform appearance in documents with predefined styles.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Ensures readability and professionalism in formal documents.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Prevents formatting conflicts when pasting content from external sources.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tips for Efficient Formatting in MS Word:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Use styles and templates for consistent formatting across the document.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Familiarize yourself with shortcut keys to speed up the editing process.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Leverage the Format Painter tool to copy formatting from one section to another.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following are the types of Read-Only Memory (ROM)?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;i. MROM&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;ii. PROM&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;iii. EPROM&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;iv. EEPROM&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;v. Flash memory&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;All i, ii, iii, iv, and v&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Read-Only Memory (ROM) is a type of non-volatile memory used in computers and other electronic devices to store data permanently, even when the device is powered off.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The following are the types of ROM:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;MROM (Masked ROM):&lt;/strong&gt; The original form of ROM, programmed during manufacturing and cannot be altered later.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;PROM (Programmable ROM):&lt;/strong&gt; Can be programmed by the user once using a special device, but cannot be reprogrammed.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;EPROM (Erasable Programmable ROM):&lt;/strong&gt; Can be erased by exposing it to ultraviolet light and reprogrammed multiple times.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;EEPROM (Electrically Erasable Programmable ROM):&lt;/strong&gt; Can be erased and reprogrammed using electrical signals, allowing for multiple updates.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Flash Memory:&lt;/strong&gt; A modern and widely used form of EEPROM, allowing fast and efficient erasing and rewriting of data.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;All the above types of ROM play a significant role in data storage and retrieval in various applications.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Comparison of ROM Types:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;MROM:&lt;/strong&gt; Cost-effective but inflexible due to its permanent programming.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;PROM:&lt;/strong&gt; Allows user programming but cannot be altered once programmed.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;EPROM:&lt;/strong&gt; Provides flexibility with erasing and reprogramming, but requires special equipment for erasure.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;EEPROM:&lt;/strong&gt; Offers electrical erasure and reprogramming, making it more convenient than EPROM.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Flash Memory:&lt;/strong&gt; Combines the advantages of EEPROM with faster operation, widely used in modern devices like USB drives and SSDs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;MROM:&lt;/strong&gt; Used in older devices where fixed programming is sufficient.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;PROM:&lt;/strong&gt; Suitable for firmware and applications requiring single-time programming.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;EPROM and EEPROM:&lt;/strong&gt; Utilized in embedded systems and devices requiring occasional updates.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Flash Memory:&lt;/strong&gt; Found in smartphones, cameras, and computers due to its high speed and capacity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Advantages of ROM:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Non-volatile memory ensures data retention even after power is turned off.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Reliable for storing critical system instructions such as firmware.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Variety of ROM types available to suit specific application needs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

